---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What grade do I need to pass a class?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "It depends on your current grade, your target grade, and how much coursework remains. This guide shows how to calculate it step by step."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What is a passing grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Most schools consider 60% or higher a passing grade, but some classes require 70%."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<GuideLayout
  title="What Grade Do I Need to Pass a Class? (Step-by-Step Guide)"
  description="Find out what grade you need to pass your class. Learn the formula and use our calculator to get your answer instantly."
  slug="/what-grade-do-i-need-to-pass-a-class"
  heroTitle="What Grade Do I Need to Pass a Class?"
  heroText="If you're trying to figure out whether you can still pass your class, this guide shows you exactly how to calculate what you need."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
>
  <div class="card">
    <p>
      One of the most common questions students ask is
      <strong> what grade do I need to pass? </strong>
      The answer depends on your current grade, your target grade, and how much
      of your class is left.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Step 1: Know Your Current Grade</h2>
    <p>
      Start by finding your current average in the class. This is usually shown
      in your gradebook.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Step 2: Know the Passing Grade</h2>
    <p>
      Most schools consider <strong>60% or higher</strong> a passing grade,
      but some classes require <strong>70%</strong>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Step 3: Know What's Left</h2>
    <p>
      Determine how much of your class grade is still remaining. This could be
      your final exam, projects, or assignments.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Step 4: Use the Formula</h2>
    <p>A simple way to think about it is:</p>
    <p><strong>(Target Grade - Current Contribution) / Remaining Weight</strong></p>
    <p>
      Instead of doing this manually, use the calculator below.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/what-grade-do-i-need-calculator/">Use the What Grade Do I Need Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Example</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Current grade: 65%</li>
      <li>Passing grade: 70%</li>
      <li>Remaining coursework: 30%</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      You may need a strong score on your remaining work to pass.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What If You Need Over 100%?</h2>
    <p>
      If your result is above 100%, your goal may not be possible unless extra
      credit is available.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Final Tip</h2>
    <p>
      Don't wait until the last minute. Check your grade early and plan ahead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Try these tools:
      <a href="/grade-calculator/"> Grade Calculator</a> |
      <a href="/final-exam-calculator/"> Final Exam Calculator</a> |
      <a href="/weighted-grade-calculator/"> Weighted Grade Calculator</a> |
      <a href="/gpa-calculator/"> GPA Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</GuideLayout>
